{{expand language|topic=|langcode=ka|otherarticle=ეროვნული ფორუმი|date=September 2017}}
{{refimprove|date=September 2017}}
The '''National Forum''' ({{lang-ka|ეროვნული ფორუმი}}, ''erovnuli p'orumi'') is a political party in [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] established on December 15, 2006 by the former diplomat [[Kakha Shartava]]. He is the son of [[Zhiuli Shartava]], a Georgian politician in [[Abkhazia]], killed by the Abkhaz militias during the [[War in Abkhazia (1992–93)|secessionist war]] in the region in 1993. Several veteran politicians such as [[Revaz Shavishvili]], [[Irakli Melashvili]] and [[Gubaz Sanikidze]] also joined the party.<ref>[http://www.civil.ge/eng/article.php?id=14304 New Opposition Party Established.] ''Civil Georgia''. December 15, 2006.</ref> <br /> 
Party political council of the organizational members are: Kakhaber Shartava, Gubaz Sanikidze, Revaz Shavishvili, Irakli Melashvili, Nodar Javakhishvili and Irakli Gobejishvili. A leading Party member was economic expert Niko Orvelashvili  who died on 15 January 2010.<br />
The party advocates a [[parliamentary republic]] as a form of government in Georgia. Unlike most other Georgian political parties, it does not support Georgia’s aspiration to join [[NATO]], and argues Georgia should be a "neutral country."<ref>[http://www.geotimes.ge/index.php?m=home&newsid=3358 Tbilisi Sees Russia's Hands behind Anti-NATO Campaign in Georgia.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722174358/http://www.geotimes.ge/index.php?m=home&newsid=3358 |date=2011-07-22 }} ''The Georgian Times''. February 27, 2007.</ref> The National Forum was a member of the United Opposition alliance which staged mass [[2007 Georgian demonstrations|anti-government demonstrations]] in November 2007 and ran on an opposition ticket in the [[Georgian legislative election, 2008|parliamentary election]] in May 2008. For the 2012 elections it was part of the [[Georgian Dream]] alliance that won the election against United National Movement. On April 3, 2016 National Forum left coalition after party convention, majority of members voted to leave [[Georgian Dream]]

