'''RRS ''James Clark Ross''''' is a supply and research ship operated by the [[British Antarctic Survey]].
==History== [[Royal Research Ship|RRS]] ''James Clark Ross'' is named after the English explorer [[James Clark Ross]].<ref name=bas>{{cite web| url=http://www.antarctica.ac.uk/living_and_working/research_ships/rrs_james_clark_ross/| title=RRS ''James Clark Ross''| publisher=[[British Antarctic Survey]]| accessdate=2007-11-24}}</ref> She replaced the {{ship|RRS|John Biscoe|1956|6}} in 1991.
In March 2018, RRS ''James Clark Ross'' was due to sample the marine life around the world's biggest iceberg, [[Iceberg A-68|A-68]], but was unable to reach the site due to thick sea ice in the Weddell Sea.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-43257289| title=Mission to giant A-68 berg thwarted by sea-ice| publisher=BBC News| author=Jonathan Amos| date=2 March 2018| accessdate=12 April 2018}}</ref>
==See also== * {{ship|RRS|Ernest Shackleton}}, another British Antarctic Survey [[Royal Research Ship]]. * [[RRS Sir David Attenborough|RRS ''Sir David Attenborough'']], a new Royal Research Ship planned to enter service in 2019. * [[James Ross Island]]
